Scotland, United Kingdom":"Crieff, Perthshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","Blackford, Perthshire, Scotland":"Blackford, Perthshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1340–1413":"1340–1413","–1376":"–1376","1352–1384":"1352–1384","1368–1424":"1368–1424","1274–1329":"1274–1329","1413":"1413","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1376":"1376","1352":"1352","1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1274":"1274","1329":"1329","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kincardine, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kincardine, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Crieff, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Crieff, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Blackford, Perthshire, Scotland":"Blackford, Perthshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1340–1413":"1340–1413","–1376":"–1376","1352–1384":"1352–1384","1368–1424":"1368–1424","1274–1329":"1274–1329","1413":"1413","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1376":"1376","1352":"1352","1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1274":"1274","1329":"1329","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Kincardine, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kincardine, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Crieff, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Crieff, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Blackford, Perthshire, Scotland":"Blackford, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Graham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, recorded in Domesday Book as <i>Graham</i> (as well as <i>Grantham</i>, <i>Grandham</i>, and <i>Granham</i>). See also   Grantham  .","Irish (especially Ulster): in Ireland <i>Graham</i> is generally the Scottish name, but it has additionally been adopted as an Anglicized form of both <b>Ó Creacháin</b> (see   Crehan  ) and <b>Ó Gormghaile</b> (see   Gormley  ).","History: The surname Graham was taken to Scotland at the beginning of the 12th century by the Norman baron William de Graham, holder of the manor of Grantham in Lincolnshire, from whom many if not all modern bearers are probably descended. The chief of Clan Graham is the Duke of Montrose."],"variants":[{"name":"Greim","meanings":["South German: from a short form of a compound personal name beginning with the element <i>grīm</i> ‘mask, helmet’.","Scottish: variant of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahm","meanings":["(1997: 107;2007: 460; 2010: NA)","Scottish (Lanarkshire and northern England): shortened form of   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grantham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire and East Yorkshire): habitational name from Grantham in Lincolnshire, of uncertain origin. The final element is Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’; the first may be Old English <i>grand</i> ‘gravel’ or perhaps a personal name <i>Granta</i>, which probably originated as a byname meaning ‘snarler’. See also   Graham  ."]},{"name":"Grahame","meanings":["(1997: 113;2007: 164; 2010: NA)","Scottish: variant of   Graham  . — Note: The population figure published by the US Census Bureau for this surname in the year 2000 is as high as 261, while the figure for 2010 is supposedly lower than 100."]}]},{"name":"Patrick","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Name of the apostle and patron saint of Ireland (  <i>c.</i>389–461 ), Gaelic <i>Pádraig</i>. He was a Christian Briton and a Roman citizen, who as a young man was captured and enslaved by raiders from Ireland. He escaped and went to Gaul before returning home to Britain. In about  419  he felt a call to do missionary work in Ireland. He studied for twelve years at Auxerre, and in  432  returned to Ireland. For the rest of his life it is difficult to distinguish fact from fiction. He apparently went to the court of the high kings at Tara and made some converts there; then he travelled around Ireland making further converts until about  445 , when he established his archiepiscopal see at Armagh. By the time of his death almost the whole of Ireland is said to have been converted to Christianity. He is also credited with codifying the laws of Ireland. In his Latin autobiography, as well as in later tradition, his name appears as <i>Patricius</i> ‘patrician’ (i.e. belonging to the Roman senatorial or noble class), but this may actually represent a Latinized form of some lost Celtic (British) name. In Ireland in particular, it has been one of the most enduringly popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Patrick Graham was born in 1340, in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of David de Graham Laird of Dundaff. He had at least 1 son with Matilda Maud Blackford. He died in 1413, in Crieff, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 73."},"et":{"1340–1413":"1340–1413","–1376":"–1376","1352–1384":"1352–1384","1368–1424":"1368–1424","1274–1329":"1274–1329","1413":"1413","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1376":"1376","1352":"1352","1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1274":"1274","1329":"1329","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Kincardine, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kincardine, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Crieff, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Crieff, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Blackford, Perthshire, Scotland":"Blackford, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1340–1413":"1340–1413","–1376":"–1376","1352–1384":"1352–1384","1368–1424":"1368–1424","1274–1329":"1274–1329","1413":"1413","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1376":"1376","1352":"1352","1340":"1340","1384":"1384","1274":"1274","1329":"1329","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kincardine, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Kincardine, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Crieff, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Crieff, Perthshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kunin